
⚙️ Nonlinear Spring Equilibrium Using Bisection Method (MATLAB)
This project solves for the equilibrium displacement of a nonlinear spring subjected to a constant force using the Bisection method in MATLAB.
The spring contains a cubic stiffness component, making the system nonlinear. The equilibrium displacement is calculated iteratively by finding the root of the force residual equation.
📘 Problem Description
Given:
 * Linear stiffness: k = 100
 * Cubic stiffness: beta = 40
 * Applied Force: P = 50
Using the balance of internal spring resistance and external applied force, we obtain the residual force equation:
This nonlinear equation is solved for x (displacement) when f(x) = 0 using the Bisection method.
🧠 Method Used
Bisection Update Equation:
Where:
 * x_l = Lower bound (Initially 0)
 * x_u = Upper bound (Initially 1.3)
 * x_r = Midpoint (Current root estimate)
 * y_l and y_r = Function evaluations at x_l and x_r
 * Convergence condition: Loop continues while |x_u - x_l| > [span_13](start_span)0.01
The bounds are updated based on the sign of y_l \times y_r. If the product is negative, x_u = x_r; otherwise, x_l = x_r.
🛠 MATLAB Code
clc; clear; close all;

k = 100;    % Linear stiffness
beta = 40;  % Cubic stiffness
P = 50;     % Applied Force


xl = 0;    
xu = 1.3;  
err = 0.01;
iter = 1;
data = [];


while abs(xu - xl) > err
    xr = (xl + xu) / 2;
    
    
    yl = k*xl + beta*xl^3 - P;
    yr = k*xr + beta*xr^3 - P;
    
    
    data(iter, :) = [xl xr xu yl yr];
    
    
    if yl * yr < 0
        xu = xr;
    else
        xl = xr;
    end
    iter = iter + 1;
end

root = xr;
disp('   xl       xr       xu       yl       yr');
disp(data);
fprintf('Displacement Root = %f m\n', root);


x_vals = linspace(0, 1.3, 300);
y_vals = k*x_vals + beta*x_vals.^3 - P;

figure;
plot(x_vals, y_vals, 'LineWidth', 1.5); hold on;
plot(root, 0, 'ro', 'MarkerSize', 8, 'MarkerFaceColor', 'r');
grid on;
xlabel('Displacement (x)');
ylabel('Force Residual (f(x))');
title('Nonlinear Spring Equilibrium Root');


📊 Output
The program displays:
 * A data table showing the tracking of variables (x_l, x_r, x_u, y_l, y_r) across all iterations.
 * Final value of the calculated Displacement Root.
 * A generated plot of the Force Residual vs. Displacement curve, with the exact equilibrium root marked with a red dot.
🚀 How to Run
 * Open MATLAB
 * Create a new script file (e.g., nonlinear_spring_bisection.m)
 * Paste the code
 * Run the script
